input.content:
{
  "week": "Week 10",
  "dateRange": "22 December - 28 December",
  "topics": [
    {
      "id": "abnormality-classification",
      "title": "Defining Abnormality and Classification Systems",
      "subtitle": "Understanding Mental Disorders",
      "summary": "Abnormality can be defined in multiple ways, including deviation from statistical norms, societal norms, ideal mental health, personal distress, causing distress to others, maladaptiveness, and unexpected behavior. The DSM-5 and ICD provide standardized classification systems for mental disorders.",
      "keyTakeaways": [
        "Multiple criteria define abnormality: statistical deviation, norm violation, personal distress, maladaptiveness, and unexpectedness.",
        "Kraepelin's 1883 work laid the foundation for modern classification systems.",
        "DSM-5 and ICD are the two major classification systems for mental disorders.",
        "Classification helps with diagnosis, treatment planning, and research but has limitations.",
        "The 'Four Ds' (Deviance, Distress, Dysfunction, Danger) are commonly used criteria for abnormality."
      ],
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "What is Abnormality?"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Defining abnormality is complex and multifaceted. No single criterion is sufficient; instead, mental health professionals consider multiple perspectives."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Seven Approaches to Defining Abnormality",
          "items": [
            "Statistical Deviation: Behavior that is statistically rare. However, this is problematic—giftedness is rare but not abnormal, and common issues like anxiety can be disorders.",
            "Deviation from Social Norms: Violating society's standards of acceptable behavior. Problem: Is rule-breaking the same as having a disorder? Cultural variation matters.",
            "Deviation from Ideal Mental Health: Falling short of optimal psychological functioning. However, ideal mental health varies significantly across cultures.",
            "Personal Distress: Experiencing subjective suffering, such as anxiety or depression. Example: Obsessive-compulsive behaviors causing significant distress.",
            "Distress to Others: Causing interpersonal problems or distress. Example: Narcissistic personality disorder affecting relationships.",
            "Maladaptiveness: Behavior that interferes with daily functioning or well-being. Example: Substance use impairing work and relationships.",
            "Unexpectedness: Behavior that is out of proportion to the situation. Example: Anxiety in anxiety disorders is excessive relative to actual threat."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "Info",
          "title": "The Four Ds",
          "text": "Mental health professionals commonly use four criteria to define abnormality: Deviance (statistical/social), Distress (personal suffering), Dysfunction (impaired functioning), and Danger (to self or others). Most disorders meet multiple criteria."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Classification Systems: DSM and ICD"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Emil Kraepelin published the first recognized textbook of psychiatry in 1883, claiming that certain groups of symptoms occur together sufficiently often to be called a 'disease' or syndrome. His classification formed the basis for the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) and the International Classification of Diseases (ICD)."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Key Features of Modern Classification",
          "items": [
            "DSM-5: Published by the American Psychiatric Association, primarily used in the United States. Provides detailed diagnostic criteria for each disorder.",
            "ICD-11: Published by the World Health Organization, used internationally for all diseases including mental disorders.",
            "Both systems use categorical classification with specific criteria that must be met for diagnosis.",
            "Classification facilitates communication among professionals, guides treatment, and enables research."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "DSM-5 Structure"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The DSM-5 organizes mental disorders into 20 major categories, each containing multiple specific disorders."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Major DSM-5 Categories (Selected)",
          "items": [
            "I. Neurodevelopmental Disorders (e.g., ADHD, Autism Spectrum Disorder)",
            "II. Schizophrenia Spectrum and Other Psychotic Disorders",
            "III. Bipolar and Related Disorders",
            "IV. Depressive Disorders",
            "V. Anxiety Disorders",
            "VI. Obsessive-Compulsive and Related Disorders",
            "VII. Trauma- and Stressor-Related Disorders",
            "X. Feeding and Eating Disorders",
            "XVI. Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders",
            "XVIII. Personality Disorders"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Example: Major Depressive Disorder Criteria"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "A person must experience at least 5 symptoms during the same 2-week period, representing a change from previous functioning. At least one symptom must be: (1) depressed mood or (2) loss of interest/pleasure."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "DSM-5 Symptoms for Major Depression",
          "items": [
            "Depressed mood most of the day, nearly every day",
            "Markedly reduced interest or pleasure in most activities",
            "Significant unintentional weight loss or gain, or change in appetite",
            "Insomnia or hypersomnia",
            "Observable psychomotor agitation or slowing",
            "Fatigue or loss of energy",
            "Feelings of worthlessness or excessive/inappropriate guilt",
            "Reduced ability to think, concentrate, or make decisions",
            "Recurrent thoughts of death, suicidal ideation, or suicide attempt"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Additionally, symptoms must cause clinically significant distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other important areas of functioning."
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "AlertCircle",
          "title": "Limitations of Classification",
          "text": "Classification systems don't always work perfectly. Comorbidity (multiple disorders), dimensional variation (mild to severe), and individual differences can make categorical diagnosis challenging. Some argue for dimensional rather than categorical approaches."
        }
      ],
      "questions": [
        {
          "question": "Which criterion for abnormality is illustrated by someone with severe social anxiety experiencing intense fear and avoidance that prevents them from attending school or work?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Statistical deviation only",
            "Personal distress and dysfunction (maladaptiveness)",
            "Deviation from social norms only",
            "Unexpectedness only"
          ],
          "answer": "Personal distress and dysfunction (maladaptiveness)",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "This person shows TWO criteria for abnormality working together:\n\n**1. Personal Distress:**\n- The person experiences INTENSE FEAR (an unpleasant emotional state)\n- This fear causes SUFFERING - they're not comfortable with their anxiety\n- The distress is ONGOING, not a one-time event\n\n**2. Dysfunction/Maladaptiveness:**\n- They CANNOT ATTEND school or work (major life activities are impaired)\n- Their behavior (avoidance) INTERFERES with daily functioning\n- This is a measurable impairment: 0 days at school/work vs. expected attendance\n\n**Why multiple criteria matter:** Most mental disorders meet MORE than one criterion. This case clearly shows both suffering (personal distress) AND inability to function normally (dysfunction). If someone was statistically rare but functioning fine and not suffering, we wouldn't call it a disorder.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Statistical deviation only": "Statistical deviation means behavior that is RARE in the population. PROBLEM: The scenario emphasizes the person's SUFFERING and INABILITY TO FUNCTION, not how common or rare their anxiety is. Also, 'only' ignores the clear dysfunction and distress present. Anxiety disorders are actually quite common (affecting ~20% of people), so statistical rarity isn't the key issue here.",
              "Deviation from social norms only": "Social norm deviation means BREAKING SOCIETY'S RULES about acceptable behavior. PROBLEM: Having anxiety isn't rule-breaking - the person might follow every social norm while still experiencing crippling internal fear. Someone can be polite, law-abiding, and still have severe social anxiety. The scenario describes internal suffering and functional impairment, not norm violation.",
              "Unexpectedness only": "Unexpectedness means the reaction is OUT OF PROPORTION to the actual situation. While social anxiety IS disproportionate (the social situation isn't actually dangerous), the scenario specifically highlights TWO things: (1) intense fear and suffering, (2) inability to function. 'Only' unexpectedness ignores these explicit features. The most complete answer includes both distress AND dysfunction."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "What was Emil Kraepelin's key contribution to understanding mental disorders?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "He developed the first intelligence test",
            "He showed that symptoms often cluster together into recognizable syndromes",
            "He invented psychoanalysis",
            "He discovered neurotransmitters"
          ],
          "answer": "He showed that symptoms often cluster together into recognizable syndromes",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**Kraepelin's Discovery (1883):**\n\nKraepelin noticed a PATTERN: certain symptoms appear TOGETHER in the same patients, again and again.\n\n**How he figured this out:**\n1. He observed hundreds of psychiatric patients\n2. He noticed certain symptom combinations kept recurring\n3. Example: Patients with hallucinations often ALSO had delusions AND disorganized thinking\n4. He called these recurring combinations 'syndromes' or 'diseases'\n\n**Why this mattered:**\n- BEFORE Kraepelin: Mental illness was viewed as one general 'madness'\n- AFTER Kraepelin: We could identify DISTINCT disorders by their symptom patterns\n- This led directly to the DSM and ICD classification systems we use today\n\n**Concrete example:** Depression symptoms (sad mood, sleep problems, appetite changes, fatigue) tend to occur TOGETHER. This clustering is what makes 'Major Depression' a recognizable syndrome, not just random symptoms.",
            "incorrect": {
              "He developed the first intelligence test": "That was Alfred BINET in 1905, not Kraepelin. Binet created the first IQ test to identify children needing educational help. Kraepelin worked on CLASSIFYING mental disorders, not measuring intelligence. These are completely different areas of psychology.",
              "He invented psychoanalysis": "That was Sigmund FREUD (late 1800s-early 1900s), not Kraepelin. Psychoanalysis is a TREATMENT approach focusing on unconscious conflicts. Kraepelin worked on DIAGNOSIS and CLASSIFICATION - figuring out what different mental disorders ARE, not how to treat them with therapy.",
              "He discovered neurotransmitters": "Neurotransmitter discoveries came from NEUROCHEMISTRY research in the mid-20th century (1920s-1960s). Otto Loewi discovered the first neurotransmitter in 1921. Kraepelin worked in the 1880s without knowledge of brain chemistry. He classified disorders based on observable symptoms, not brain mechanisms."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "According to DSM-5 criteria, what is the minimum number of symptoms and time period required for diagnosing Major Depressive Disorder?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "3 symptoms for 1 week",
            "5 symptoms for 2 weeks",
            "7 symptoms for 4 weeks",
            "9 symptoms for 6 weeks"
          ],
          "answer": "5 symptoms for 2 weeks",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**DSM-5 Criteria for Major Depressive Disorder:**\n\n**NUMBER: At least 5 symptoms**\n- DSM-5 lists 9 possible symptoms\n- You need AT LEAST 5 of these 9 to qualify\n- One of the 5 MUST be either: (a) depressed mood, OR (b) loss of interest/pleasure\n\n**DURATION: 2 weeks minimum**\n- Symptoms must be present for the SAME 2-week period\n- This rules out normal brief sadness (a few bad days)\n- The 2 weeks must show a CHANGE from previous functioning\n\n**ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENT:**\n- Symptoms must cause significant distress OR impairment in work/social/other functioning\n\n**Why these thresholds?** They distinguish clinical depression from normal sadness. Everyone has sad days, but 5+ symptoms lasting 2+ weeks with functional impairment indicates something beyond normal grief or stress response.",
            "incorrect": {
              "3 symptoms for 1 week": "TOO FEW symptoms (need 5, not 3) and TOO SHORT duration (need 2 weeks, not 1). Why these minimums matter: Normal sadness after a bad week might cause 2-3 symptoms briefly. The 5-symptom, 2-week threshold ensures we're identifying a clinical syndrome, not normal emotional fluctuation.",
              "7 symptoms for 4 weeks": "TOO MANY symptoms required (5, not 7) and TOO LONG duration (2 weeks, not 4). This would miss many people with genuine depression. The DSM-5 uses MINIMUM thresholds - you CAN have 7+ symptoms, and they CAN last 4+ weeks, but the MINIMUMS are 5 symptoms and 2 weeks.",
              "9 symptoms for 6 weeks": "WAY too stringent. While the DSM-5 lists 9 possible symptoms, you only need 5 OF those 9 (not all 9). Duration is 2 weeks (not 6). This answer would severely underdiagnose depression - waiting 6 weeks with 9 symptoms would mean missing people who need help earlier."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "A person who is intellectually gifted (IQ of 145) is statistically rare. According to the material on defining abnormality, why is this NOT considered abnormal?",
          "difficulty": "tricky",
          "options": [
            "It doesn't cause distress, dysfunction, or represent a deficit",
            "Giftedness is socially valued, so it cannot be abnormal",
            "IQ tests are invalid for measuring abnormality",
            "Statistical rarity alone is sufficient to define abnormality"
          ],
          "answer": "It doesn't cause distress, dysfunction, or represent a deficit",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**Why statistical rarity ALONE doesn't equal abnormality:**\n\nGiftedness IS statistically rare (IQ 145 = top 0.1% of population). But check the OTHER criteria:\n\n**Does it cause personal DISTRESS?** No\n- Gifted people don't suffer FROM being gifted\n- High IQ itself doesn't cause emotional pain\n\n**Does it cause DYSFUNCTION?** No\n- Gifted people function well (often BETTER than average)\n- They can work, have relationships, live independently\n\n**Is it a DEFICIT (something missing)?** No\n- It's an ADVANTAGE, not a loss of function\n- Nothing is impaired or diminished\n\n**The lesson:** Statistical rarity is just ONE possible criterion. To be considered a mental disorder, you need ADDITIONAL criteria - typically distress, dysfunction, or danger. Being rare but advantaged isn't a disorder. Being rare, suffering, AND unable to function? That might be.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Giftedness is socially valued, so it cannot be abnormal": "Social value ISN'T the core reason. Consider: If something rare was socially DEvalued but caused no distress or dysfunction, would it be a disorder? No - because the KEY criteria are distress, dysfunction, and danger, NOT social approval. A rare trait that's disliked but causes no problems still isn't a mental disorder.",
              "IQ tests are invalid for measuring abnormality": "This MISSES the point entirely. The issue isn't whether IQ tests are valid - they reliably measure cognitive ability. The issue is that statistical rarity (which IQ tests DO measure) is INSUFFICIENT ALONE to define abnormality. The test is valid; the criterion of 'rarity alone' is insufficient.",
              "Statistical rarity alone is sufficient to define abnormality": "This is the OPPOSITE of what the material teaches. The giftedness example exists specifically to DISPROVE this statement. If rarity alone defined abnormality, gifted people would have a mental disorder - which is clearly absurd. You need rarity PLUS distress, dysfunction, or danger."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Which of the following is a limitation of categorical classification systems like the DSM-5?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "They don't provide any diagnostic criteria",
            "They make communication between professionals impossible",
            "They struggle with comorbidity and dimensional variation in symptom severity",
            "They only classify physical diseases, not mental disorders"
          ],
          "answer": "They struggle with comorbidity and dimensional variation in symptom severity",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**Two major limitations of categorical systems:**\n\n**1. COMORBIDITY problem:**\n- Comorbidity = having MULTIPLE disorders at once\n- Example: Someone has depression AND anxiety AND substance use disorder\n- Categorical systems treat these as separate 'boxes'\n- Reality: These conditions overlap and interact\n- The neat categories don't capture real-life complexity\n\n**2. DIMENSIONAL VARIATION problem:**\n- Categories are YES/NO: you either HAVE depression or you DON'T\n- Reality: Symptoms exist on a SPECTRUM from mild to severe\n- Someone with 4 symptoms (just under threshold) gets 'no diagnosis'\n- Someone with 5 symptoms gets 'Major Depression'\n- But the difference between 4 and 5 symptoms may be minimal\n\n**Why this matters:** Categories are useful shortcuts, but human psychology is CONTINUOUS and COMPLEX. Forcing it into neat boxes loses important information about severity gradients and overlapping conditions.",
            "incorrect": {
              "They don't provide any diagnostic criteria": "COMPLETELY FALSE. The DSM-5's PRIMARY function is providing detailed diagnostic criteria. Each disorder has specific symptom lists, duration requirements, and exclusion criteria. That's literally what the DSM-5 IS - a manual of diagnostic criteria.",
              "They make communication between professionals impossible": "OPPOSITE of true. Classification IMPROVES communication. Before standardized systems, one psychiatrist's 'schizophrenia' might be another's 'manic depression.' Now, when a clinician says 'Major Depressive Disorder,' all professionals know exactly what criteria were met. This IS a benefit, not a limitation.",
              "They only classify physical diseases, not mental disorders": "BACKWARDS. The DSM-5 classifies MENTAL disorders specifically. The ICD classifies ALL diseases (including mental ones). This answer confuses the basic purpose of these classification systems."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In Rosenhan's 'On Being Sane in Insane Places' study, what did pseudopatients report to gain admission to psychiatric hospitals?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Severe depression and suicidal thoughts",
            "Auditory hallucinations saying 'empty,' 'hollow,' and 'thud'",
            "Paranoid delusions about government surveillance",
            "Visual hallucinations of threatening figures"
          ],
          "answer": "Auditory hallucinations saying 'empty,' 'hollow,' and 'thud'",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**The Rosenhan Study (1973) - What Actually Happened:**\n\n**Step 1: The fake symptom**\n- Pseudopatients reported hearing VOICES (auditory hallucinations)\n- The voices said three words: 'empty,' 'hollow,' 'thud'\n- These words were intentionally VAGUE and existential\n- This was the ONLY false symptom reported\n\n**Step 2: After admission**\n- Once inside the hospital, they acted COMPLETELY NORMAL\n- They stopped reporting any symptoms\n- They behaved normally, talked normally, followed rules\n\n**Step 3: The disturbing finding**\n- Staff NEVER identified them as fakes\n- They were kept for an average of 19 days\n- All were diagnosed with schizophrenia (except one: manic-depression)\n- Their normal behavior was interpreted through the lens of their 'diagnosis'\n\n**The point:** Vague symptoms + psychiatric setting = diagnosis, even without real illness.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Severe depression and suicidal thoughts": "NO depression or suicidal thoughts were reported. The pseudopatients specifically reported ONLY auditory hallucinations with the words 'empty,' 'hollow,' and 'thud.' The study was designed with minimal, unusual symptoms to test how easily admission could be gained.",
              "Paranoid delusions about government surveillance": "NO paranoid content was reported. The hallucinations were vague words ('empty,' 'hollow,' 'thud') without any paranoid theme. The researchers avoided complex symptom presentations to make the study cleaner - just one simple false symptom.",
              "Visual hallucinations of threatening figures": "The hallucinations were AUDITORY (hearing voices), not visual. And they weren't threatening - just the words 'empty,' 'hollow,' 'thud.' The researchers chose these vague words because they had no clear diagnostic meaning, testing whether even ambiguous symptoms led to diagnosis."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "What was the key finding of Rosenhan's study regarding psychiatric staff's ability to identify the pseudopatients?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Staff correctly identified all pseudopatients within 24 hours",
            "Staff could not distinguish pseudopatients from actual patients",
            "Only psychiatrists could identify them, but nurses could not",
            "Pseudopatients were identified by their lack of medication side effects"
          ],
          "answer": "Staff could not distinguish pseudopatients from actual patients",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**The Shocking Finding:**\n\nPsychiatric staff COULD NOT tell that the pseudopatients were mentally healthy.\n\n**What happened:**\n- Pseudopatients acted completely NORMAL after admission\n- They talked, ate, slept, and behaved like normal people\n- Staff interpreted ALL their behavior through the 'illness' lens\n- Example: Note-taking was recorded as 'patient engages in writing behavior' (as if it were a symptom)\n\n**Key statistics:**\n- Average hospitalization: 19 days (range: 7-52 days)\n- ALL were admitted and diagnosed\n- NONE were identified as fakes by staff\n- Interestingly: 35% of REAL patients suspected the pseudopatients were fakes!\n\n**What this means:**\n- Once labeled 'mentally ill,' normal behavior looks abnormal\n- Context (psychiatric hospital) shapes interpretation of behavior\n- Staff expected to see illness, so they saw illness",
            "incorrect": {
              "Staff correctly identified all pseudopatients within 24 hours": "The OPPOSITE happened. Staff NEVER identified them, even after weeks. The pseudopatients had to be 'discharged' by the researchers contacting the hospitals. Staff didn't catch on even when pseudopatients acted completely normal for weeks.",
              "Only psychiatrists could identify them, but nurses could not": "NO staff identified them - not psychiatrists, not nurses, not attendants. Ironically, REAL PATIENTS sometimes suspected the pseudopatients were faking: 'You're not crazy. You're a journalist or professor checking up on the hospital.'",
              "Pseudopatients were identified by their lack of medication side effects": "Pseudopatients were given medication (which they secretly discarded - not swallowed). Staff didn't use medication response as a detection method. The point is that NO behavioral or medical observation led staff to question the diagnoses."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "A researcher wants to replicate Rosenhan's study. Based on the original findings, what should they expect regarding diagnosis upon admission?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Modern diagnostic criteria would prevent any false admissions",
            "Pseudopatients would likely be admitted and diagnosed, raising questions about diagnostic validity",
            "Brain imaging would immediately reveal normal brain function",
            "Structured interviews would definitively distinguish real from fake symptoms"
          ],
          "answer": "Pseudopatients would likely be admitted and diagnosed, raising questions about diagnostic validity",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**What Rosenhan's study tells us about diagnosis:**\n\n**The core problem identified:**\n- Once you're IN a psychiatric setting reporting symptoms, context biases everything\n- Clinicians EXPECT to see illness in patients who present for treatment\n- This expectation shapes how ALL behavior is interpreted\n- This is called 'confirmation bias' + 'context effects'\n\n**Why this would likely still occur:**\n1. Patients report symptoms → clinicians must take them seriously (ethical obligation)\n2. You can't prove someone ISN'T hallucinating (no objective test)\n3. Erring on the side of treatment is safer than dismissing real illness\n4. The setting (hospital, symptoms reported) creates a diagnostic frame\n\n**The validity question:**\n- If healthy people can be diagnosed as ill, what does that say about our diagnostic tools?\n- How many real patients are misdiagnosed?\n- This isn't about clinicians being bad - it's about SYSTEMIC limitations of psychiatric diagnosis",
            "incorrect": {
              "Modern diagnostic criteria would prevent any false admissions": "OPTIMISTIC but probably WRONG. Yes, DSM-5 has more specific criteria than 1970s diagnostics. But Rosenhan's point was about CONTEXT BIAS, not just criteria quality. If someone comes to a psychiatric ER saying they hear voices, clinicians still can't PROVE they're lying. The ethical default is to believe patients and provide care.",
              "Brain imaging would immediately reveal normal brain function": "Brain imaging ISN'T routinely used for psychiatric admission. Even if used, there's NO 'schizophrenia scan' - no brain image definitively shows 'this person has/doesn't have schizophrenia.' Psychiatric diagnosis remains primarily based on reported symptoms and observed behavior, not biomarkers.",
              "Structured interviews would definitively distinguish real from fake symptoms": "Structured interviews IMPROVE reliability (consistency) but can't GUARANTEE validity (accuracy). They standardize QUESTIONS, but answers still depend on what patients report. A convincing liar could potentially pass any interview. The core limitation is that we can't objectively verify internal experiences like hallucinations."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "What is the primary implication of Rosenhan's study for psychiatric classification systems?",
          "difficulty": "tricky",
          "options": [
            "Classification systems are useless and should be abandoned entirely",
            "Classification systems have limitations—context can bias diagnosis, and distinguishing normalcy from pathology is challenging",
            "Only biological tests should be used for psychiatric diagnosis",
            "Psychiatric diagnosis is perfectly accurate when proper protocols are followed"
          ],
          "answer": "Classification systems have limitations—context can bias diagnosis, and distinguishing normalcy from pathology is challenging",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "**Rosenhan's NUANCED conclusion:**\n\nThe study revealed LIMITATIONS, not total failure:\n\n**Limitation 1: Context Bias**\n- Setting influences interpretation\n- In a psychiatric hospital, normal behavior looks pathological\n- The 'patient' label becomes a lens through which ALL behavior is viewed\n\n**Limitation 2: Difficulty Distinguishing Normalcy from Pathology**\n- There's no blood test for mental illness\n- Diagnosis relies on subjective reports and behavioral observation\n- Faking symptoms (or having them resolve) is hard to detect\n\n**What this DOESN'T mean:**\n- Classification isn't USELESS (it still helps communication, treatment, research)\n- We shouldn't ABANDON diagnosis (there are real mental illnesses that need treatment)\n- But we should be HUMBLE about diagnostic certainty\n- And aware that context shapes our clinical judgments\n\n**The balanced takeaway:** Classification is useful BUT imperfect. Context matters. We should diagnose carefully, aware of potential biases.",
            "incorrect": {
